7dbe88223\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-23T19:52:59.096Z\",\"thinkingMetadata\":{\"level\":\"high\",\"disabled\":false,\"triggers\":[]},\"permissionMode\":\"acceptEdits\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"bbccfeb6-9414-411e-b70a-d937dbe88223\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli_worktree1\",\"sessionId\":\"9ba7b4a4-9be0-4ad2-b835-648269d3ebad\",\"version\":\"2.1.17\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/opencode-refactor-e2e\",\"slug\":\"wiggly-nibbling-haven\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-5-20251101\",\"id\":\"msg_012hBRH3V1n28agBKm4H7om9\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"thinking\",\"thinking\":\"The user raises a good point. If we export the transcript at `turn-start`, we'll only get the transcript content up to that point - which is before the agent has done any work. The commits happen mid-turn, AFTER the agent has created files and run git commands. So the transcript exported at `turn-start` won't include the agent's actions that led to the commit.\\n\\nThe real issue is that when the agent commits mid-turn:\\n1. `turn-start` fires → transcript is exported (empty or minimal)\\n2. Agent creates files, runs commands\\n3. Agent runs `git commit`\\n4. `post-commit` fires → tries to read transcript for condensation\\n5. But the transcript file still has the OLD content from step 1!\\n\\nThe transcript needs to be refreshed/exported right before condensation reads it. This means we need to export the transcript when `post-commit` is about to condense, not at `turn-start`.\\n\\nThe proper fix would be:\\n1. Have OpenCode implement `TranscriptPreparer` interface\\n2. Call `PrepareTranscript` in the condensation code path before reading the transcript\\n\\nOr alternatively:\\n1. In the condensation code, check if the agent is OpenCode and call `opencode export` to refresh the transcript\\n\\nLet me think about this more carefully...\\n\\nActually, looking at the agent interface in agent.go:\\n\\n```go\\n// TranscriptPreparer is called before ReadTranscript to handle agent-specific\\n// flush/sync requirements (e.g., Claude Code's async transcript writing).\\n// The framework calls PrepareTranscript before ReadTranscript if implemented.\\ntype TranscriptPreparer interface {\\n    Agent\\n\\n    // PrepareTranscript ensures the transcript is ready to read.\\n    // For Claude Code, this waits for the async transcript flush to complete.\\n    PrepareTranscript(sessionRef string) error\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThis is exactly what we need! OpenCode should implement `TranscriptPreparer`, and `PrepareTranscript` should call `opencode export` to refresh the transcript.\\n\\n\\nThe condensation code path bypasses the normal lifecycle handlers, so it reads the transcript directly from `state.TranscriptPath` without calling `PrepareTranscript`. I need to modify the condensation logic to invoke `PrepareTranscript` before accessing the transcript, ensuring OpenCode has a chance to export the latest content. If agent implements TranscriptPreparer, wait for transcript to be ready\\nif preparer, ok := ag.(agent.TranscriptPreparer); ok {\\n    if err := preparer.PrepareTranscript(transcriptRef); err != nil {\\n        fmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, \\\"Warning: failed to prepare transcript: %v\\\\n\\\", err)\\n    }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThis only runs in `handleLifecycleTurnEnd`. The condensation path through `PostCommit` lacks direct agent access since it's invoked from a git hook rather than an agent hook. The session state contains `TranscriptPath` but for OpenCode, the file needs refreshing before reading. I could store the agent name in session state to determine if `opencode export` should be called, or make transcript refresh automatic by checking file age. The most straightforward approach might be checking in `extractSessionDataFromLiveTranscript` whether the transcript needs preparation before reading it. up the agent by name and call RefreshTranscript if implemented.\\n\\nThe `TranscriptPreparer` interface already exists for this purpose. I need to have OpenCode implement it, then in the condensation code, look up the agent and call `PrepareTranscript` if available. In `PostCommit`, I have access to `GetCurrentHookAgent()` for agent hooks, but for git hooks I need a different approach. Since `state.AgentType` contains the agent type string, I can search through registered agents to find a matching one and use its transcript preparation method.\\n\\nThe agent registry provides `Get(name AgentName)` to retrieve agents by name and `List()` to get all registered names. However, there's a mismatch: the session state stores `AgentType` (the display name like \\\"OpenCode\\\") rather than `AgentName` (the registry key). I'll need to either store the registry key in session state or add a lookup method to find agents by their display type.\\n\\nLooking at the SessionState struct, it currently only holds `AgentType` as a string. The cleanest approach is to add an `AgentName` field to track the registry key, populate it during session initialization, then use it to look up the agent and call `PrepareTranscript` when condensing. But the real issue the user is highlighting is that exporting at turn-start only captures the transcript up to that moment, missing the steps that follow until the commit happens.\\n\\nThe export timing is critical—it needs to occur right before condensation reads the transcript, not before the agent executes its work. This means OpenCode should implement the TranscriptPreparer interface and have the condensation code path invoke PrepareTranscript at the appropriate moment.\",\"signature\":\"\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":10,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":129,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":143186,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":129},\"output_tokens\":3,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CY